Media notes: This Blackburnian warbler was seen for ID though we were not sure if it was a drab male or colorful female.  It was in the same location as the photographs though we are not sure that it is the same individual in the photographs as in the recording.

Locality: Kemp's, Nollett Beckwith Rd, Kings CA-NS 45.12890, -64.86681

Background Species: Piranga olivacea -- Scarlet Tanager; Vireo olivaceus -- Red-eyed Vireo
Microphone: Wildtronics pro parabolic microphone, mono, amplified

Locality: Lac Hébécourt, ma cour abitibienne, station de recherche du lac Duparquet
Behaviors: Call; Feeding Young; Foraging or Eating

Observation Details: Placed observation location exactly where I eventually saw it well at 1:40 p.m., foraging on its own at the tips of the lowest hanging Doug-fir needles. Called frequently. Yellow throat and breast with slight cadmium tinge, same color to supercilium and behind ear coverts. Crown and ear coverts gray, with a bit of crescent of same yellow below eye . Black grayish with thick, long black streaks. Two narrow, white wing bars on gray wing. Two broken, long dark streaks from upper sides of breast to flanks. Lower belly and vent white with yellow wash across interface of two feather tracts.
